commit.message:
Modernize from-past-to-future.dot (so that it renders properly) (#327)

* Modernize from-past-to-future.dot

For some time now, the images in the graph haven't been rendering.
That's because:

- Using "style=invis" today prevents the node from rendering at all
  (I've opened an issue about the fact that this is apparently a change,
  and undocumented: https://gitlab.com/graphviz/graphviz/-/issues/2522)
- "shapefile" is deprecated in favor of "image"
  https://www.graphviz.org/faq/#FaqCustShape
- "shape=box" is redundant with "shapefile", as it's the only option
- With "image" (and any other node), "shape=plaintext" specifies no outline

The changes here create a graph with embedded images that have no
outlines, seemingly as the original authors intended.

* Use shape=none instead of shape=plaintext

commit.message:
Fix quoting of attribute values (#320)

* Fix needs_quotes() for values containing commas

The regular expressions underlying needs_quotes() were treating the
comma as a valid character for numeric values (presumably implying
European-style comma decimals). But in graphviz, the comma is an
attribute separator, so values containing it should always be quoted,
even if it is the current locale's decimal separator.

Replace regular expressions like `[0-9,]*` with `[0-9\.]*`, to ensure
string values containing commas are always quoted, and periods in string
values don't force quoting.

* Tests: Add unit tests for attribute value quoting

commit.message:
Move method generation to class level (#318)

Instead of generating methods in the __init__() of the class instances,
generate them as class modifications immediately after the class
definition. This allows better introspection and type checking.

* In the interactive REPL, typing `pydot.Node.<tab>` will show all
  of the generated attribute setters and getters.
* Code editors will similarly display valid completions on strings
  such as `pydot.Node.set_` or `pydot.Dot.write_`.
* Mypy's `stubgen` or `pyright --createstub` can generate type
  stubs that include the generated methods, with the correct
  commandline flags applied.

commit.message:
Massive unit testing overhaul: Parameterization, parallelization, and objects, objects, objects! (#308)

* Make unit tests discoverable

* unit tests: parameterize and parallelize

- Add the parameterize module, to build separate unit tests for
  each of the dot files in the test/my_tests and test/graphs dirs,
  for increased granularity. Test count increased from 33 to 233.
  Negligible effect on runtime (1 second).

- Add unittest-parallel, to run tests in parallel.
  Runtime reduced by over 2/3: 95s to 31s. (Intel Core i5, 4 cores).

* unit tests: Add Renderer and RenderResult classes

* unit tests: Parameterize regression tests

- Add base classes PydotTestCase and RenderedTestCase
- Split regression tests out into separate subclasses of
  RenderedTestCase (one for each directory), and generate
  their test methods from a parameterized listing of the
  directory contents
- Parameterized testcase classes use _load_test_cases() as the
  callable to list test cases (.dot files) in a given directory

* unit tests: Add TestShapeFiles class

- Split out test_graph_with_shapefiles() test into separate class
- Use unittest.skipUnless() decorator to require presence of
  datafile dir as prerequisite for test execution

* Vendor part of functools into test dir

functools.cached_property didn't exist until Python 3.8, so when
running tests under Python 3.7 we import it from test._functools
instead.

This has the unfortunate side-effect of _requiring_ that the unit
tests be executed as a package module: running the test code with
`python test/test_pydot.py` will no longer work in Python 3.7, as
the relative import of _functools will fail.

* unit tests: fix python 3.7 and 3.8 compatibility

* There's no types.GenericAlias in Python 3.7

* Black formatting fixes

* Black formatting fixes

parent 3f9a0ffde0ea5c9c80a489ae9873c6268110c647

committer GitHub <noreply@github.com> 1707558172 +0100
